  "27-42": (
    caption: [Targeting of nuclear proteins. (a) 1 A protein with an appropriate nuclear localization signal (NLS) is bound by a complex of importin (cid:6) and (cid:5). 2 The resulting complex binds to a nuclear pore and translocates. 3 Inside the nucleus, dissociation of importin (cid:5) is promoted by the binding of Ran-GTP. 4 Importin (cid:6) binds to Ran-GTP and CAS (cellular apoptosis susceptibility protein), releasing the nuclear protein. 5 Importin (cid:6) and (cid:5) and CAS are transported out of the nucleus and recy- cled. They are released in the cytosol when Ran hydrolyzes its bound GTP. 6 Ran-GDP is bound by NTF2, and transported back into the nucleus. 7 RanGEF promotes the exchange of GDP for GTP in the nucleus, and Ran-GTP is ready to process another NLS-bearing protein-importin com- plex. (b) Scanning electron micrograph of the surface of the nuclear enve- lope, showing numerous nuclear pores. The nuclear pore complex is one of the largest molecular aggregates in the cell (Mr ,5 3 107). It is made up of multiple copies of over 30 different proteins. c27ProteinMetabolism.indd Page 1145 18/10/12 11:31 AM user-F408 c27ProteinMetabolism.indd Page 1145 18/10/12 11:31 AM user-F408 /Users/user-F408/Desktop /Users/user-F408/Desktop 27.3 Protein Targeting and Degradation 1145],
